<paragraph blockId="10.[701,1228,641,1754]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
SPECIMENS: Both specimens, UAF-GS6, 7 (
<figureCitation box="[709,781,671,695]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[191,229,1236,1258]" captionTargetBox="[109,1167,210,1202]" captionTargetId="figure-182@9.[109,1167,210,1202]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 7. Photomicrographs of Bibionidae (Bibio) wings. A. UAF-GS6. B. UAF-GS7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5389472" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5389472/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">figs. 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[803,818,671,695]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[159,197,950,972]" captionTargetBox="[172,1103,210,916]" captionTargetId="figure-341@11.[171,1104,210,916]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 8. Camera lucida drawings of Bibionidae (Bibio) wings A. UAF-GS6. B. UAF-GS7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5389474" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5389474/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">8</figureCitation>
), are well preserved, with intact venation, and the dark, fuscous membrane of the wing preserved. The very dark, heavily sclerotized stigma at the apex of vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1165,1175,769,785]" fontSize="7" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">1</subScript>
was apparently not preserved (probably retained on the obverse of each specimen, which was not available). However, even the gradation in fuscous coloration is preserved (best in specimen UAF-GS7), being darkest on the costal third of the wing. Specimen UAF-GS6 has the membrane finely crenulate, which may be just preservational. The wings are 5.5 and 6.0 mm long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[701,1228,641,1754]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
DISCUSSION: The latest revision of the extant North American bibionids was by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hardy, D. E." box="[701,856,1113,1137]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="367 - 547" refId="ref6794" refString="Hardy, D. E. 1945. Revision of Nearctic Bibionidae including Neotropical Plecia and Penthetria (Diptera). University of Kansas Science Bulletin 30 (15): 367 - 547." type="journal article" year="1945">Hardy (1945)</bibRefCitation>
, in which he included 51 species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Geoffrey" authorityYear="1762" box="[847,905,1142,1166]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[847,905,1142,1166]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Bibio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; he later mentioned (
<bibRefCitation author="Hardy, D. E." pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="217 - 222" refId="ref6829" refString="Hardy, D. E. 1981. Bibionidae. In J. F. McAlpine, B. V. Peterson, G. E. Shewell, H. H. Teskey, J. R. Vockeroth and D. M. Wood (editors), Manual of Nearctic Diptera. vol. 1, 217 - 222. Ottawa, Ontario: Ministry of Supply and Services." type="journal article" year="1981">Hardy, 1981</bibRefCitation>
) that there were 53 Nearctic species. There are an approximately equal number of Palearctic species. There are at least a dozen species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Geoffrey" authorityYear="1762" box="[813,871,1260,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,871,1260,1284]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Bibio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
whose distributions extend into 
<collectingCountry box="[701,789,1289,1313]" name="Canada" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Canada</collectingCountry>
(generally to 
<collectingRegion box="[952,1038,1289,1313]" country="Canada" name="Alberta" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Alberta</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1099,1215,1289,1313]" country="Canada" name="Manitoba" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Manitoba</collectingRegion>
), and Hardy recorded four species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Geoffrey" authorityYear="1762" box="[1107,1165,1319,1343]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1107,1165,1319,1343]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Bibio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Alaska: 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1848" box="[802,1060,1348,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumipennis">
<emphasis box="[802,960,1348,1372]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">B. fumipennis</emphasis>
Walker
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Loew" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1864" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inaequalis">
<emphasis box="[1079,1227,1348,1372]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">B. inaequalis</emphasis>
Loew
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Johnson" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1929" box="[777,1056,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="labradorensis">
<emphasis box="[777,954,1378,1402]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">B. labradorensis</emphasis>
Johnson
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hardy." authorityName="Hardy." class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenellus">
<emphasis box="[1114,1228,1378,1402]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">B. tenellus</emphasis>
Hardy.
</taxonomicName>
Wing venation rarely distinguishes species in this genus, and the fossil wings are very similar to living species with one possible exception: the base of vein CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1112,1122,1505,1521]" fontSize="7" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">2</subScript>
appears separate from the base of CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1080,1090,1535,1551]" fontSize="7" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">1</subScript>
, instead of being connected by a fork at about midlength. Since a small knob on CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1018,1028,1593,1609]" fontSize="7" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">1</subScript>
occurs where the fork would normally occur, it is almost certain that this venational difference is merely preservational. Thus, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Geoffrey" authorityYear="1762" box="[949,1007,1671,1695]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[949,1007,1671,1695]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Bibio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fossils indicate that the present distribution of the genus in Alaska extended at least to the Late Miocene.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5389474" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5389474" box="[159,1097,950,972]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5389474/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" startId="11.[159,197,950,972]" targetBox="[172,1103,210,916]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph blockId="11.[159,1097,950,972]" box="[159,1097,950,972]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
